\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic sampling properties of the periodogram are well-known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "priestley:1981"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For increasingly long series: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $I(\omega_{j})/f(\omega_{j})\sim\textrm{E}$
\end_inset

 where E has a standard exponential distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $I(\omega_{j})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\omega_{k})$
\end_inset

 are independent for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ne j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is the spectral density of the underlying stationary stochastic process.
 This is a very general result, includes AR, MA and ARMA processes as special
 cases and is known to be accurate for series of moderate length, such as
 those encountered in fMRI experiments.
 If we assume that the underlying spectral density 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is smooth then we can use a smoothed version of 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\omega)$
\end_inset

, which we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\omega)$
\end_inset

, to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Testing for a response to the stimulus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spectral density estimate provides us with a baseline against which
 to test for significant departures from the underlying process.
 From (I), 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
frac
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

I(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
omega
\end_layout

\end_inset

j)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

f(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
omega
\end_layout

\end_inset

j)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
sim
\end_layout

\end_inset

 E 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:13"

\end_inset

 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\omega_{j})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\omega_{j})$
\end_inset

, we define the ratio statistic, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

, as Rj = 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
frac
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

I(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
