\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

g(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
omega
\end_layout

\end_inset

j)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset space \qquad{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \qquad{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
omega
\end_layout

\end_inset

j=j/
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
delta
\end_layout

\end_inset

 n 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:14"

\end_inset

 By calculating the statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 at the fundamental frequency of activation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

, we obtain a test statistic, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

, for significant activation.
 Large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

 indicate a large effect at the fundamental frequency.
 All of the statistics 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

, apart from 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n/2$
\end_inset

, will have the same distribution as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

 and thus can be used as a benchmark against which to compare the theoretical
 distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}$
\end_inset

, at negligible computational cost.
 Thus the method is effectively self-calibrating.
 
